\title
    %[Шаблон статьи для публикации] % Краткое название; не нужно, если полное название влезает в~колонтитул
    {Estimation of radio impulse parameters using~the~maximum~likelihood method}
\author
    %[И.\,О.~Автор] % список авторов для колонтитула; не нужен, если основной список влезает в колонтитул
    {K.\,V. Vlasova, V.\,A. Pachotin, D.\,M. Klionskiy, and~D.\,I.~Kaplun} % основной список авторов, выводимый в оглавление
    [K.\,V.~Vlasova$^1$, V.\,A.~Pachotin$^2$, D.\,M.~Klionskiy$^3$,
and~D.\,I.~Kaplun$^3$] % список авторов, выводимый в заголовок; не нужен, если он не отличается от основного
\thanks
    {The work is supported by the grant of the Russian Foundation for
Basic Research No.\,15-37-50902 and Contract No.\,02.G25.31.0058 dated 12.02.2013 (Ministry of Education and Science of Russian Federation).}
\email
    {p\_ksenia@mail.ru, VPakhotin@kantiana.ru, klio2003@list.ru, dikaplun@etu.ru}
\organization
    {$^1$Baltic Fishing Fleet State Academy, Russian Federation, Kaliningrad\par
	$^2$Immanuel Kant Baltic Federal University, Russian Federation, Kaliningrad\par
	$^3$Saint Petersburg Electrotechnical University ``LETI,'' Russian Federation, Saint Petersburg
}
\abstract
    {\noindent
The paper is devoted to the development of an algorithm for resolution and parameter estimation of radio impulses with partially overlapping spectra in the area of their
nonorthogonality (the correlation coefficient varies from 0 to 0.9). The implementation of the suggested algorithm makes it possible to design filters for resolving frequency-dependent signals and,
 therefore, to increase the capacity of a communication channel.
The maximum likelihood method has been used
to obtain analytical expressions and to perform model investigations for frequency resolution of
nonorthogonal signals. The dynamic range of signal parameter estimates has been found as a function of signal-to-noise ratio and correlation coefficient.
It has been shown that the likelihood functional value in its global minimum allows
one to estimate noise variance and the number of radio impulses in a received signal.
	

\noindent
\textbf{Keywords}: \emph{maximum-likelihood method; radio impulse, resolution;
frequency-dependent signal; communication channel; nonorthogonal signals;
signal-to-noise ratio}
}


